ntification, prevention, and amelioration of catastrophe has been largely neglected. The relationship between law and other limiting conditions—such as states of emergency—has been the subject of rich and growing literature. By contrast, little has been written about law and catastrophe. In devoting a volume to the subject, the essays' authors sketch the contours of a relatively fresh, yet crucial, terrain of inquiry. Law and Catastrophe begins the work of developing a jurisprudence of catastrophe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aDisaster reliefxLaw and legislation. 0aDisastersxLaw and legislation. 0aDisasters. 0aIndustrial accidentsxLaw and legislation. 0aSocial responsibility of business. 4aLaw -- Jurisprudence. 4aLaw -- Law and Society. 4aSociology -- Social Movements, Civil Society, and Politics. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aDouglas, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeyer, Linda Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReichman, Ravit Pe\x27er-Lamo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarat, Austin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchafer, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShamir, Ronen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmphrey, Martha Merrill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYoung, James E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804768344zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768344/original  aGBV-de